# Canvas Project Persistence

Professional creation mode project/canvas data is durable user work. Preserve these invariants:

- Every new canvas/project must persist across refreshes, returning from the home page, new browser sessions, and cloud sync.
- Each canvas must keep its own images, text items, shapes, order, title, and active selection target unless the user explicitly changes them.
- Each canvas must keep its own composer reference tray. Switching projects must load that project's pending reference images and must not leak reference images from another canvas.
- Every canvas must use the same professional creation behavior and settings. Switching projects must not change generation, editing, reference image, drag/drop, copy/paste, delete, history, or cloud sync rules.
- Generation tasks are canvas-scoped. Placeholders, in-flight task status, successful results, failed tasks, and OSS URL replacements must stay attached to the canvas where the task was started, even if the user switches to another canvas before completion.
- Canvas task completion reminders are UI-only. Status badges/toasts may indicate generating, completed, or failed tasks for another canvas, but must not auto-switch canvases, mutate generation requests, move results, or change conversation/history ownership.
- Conversation records are canvas-scoped too. User and assistant messages for a generation/edit task must be tagged with the originating canvas and the chat panel must show only the active canvas's messages.
- New conversations and history result menus are canvas-scoped. The chat panel's conversation list, active conversation, and generated-history picker must not show records from other canvases.
- Users must be able to switch between canvases and start tasks on other canvases while image/video generation is running. Do not reintroduce global generation locks for canvas switching; only block transitions that would corrupt an active text/object editing operation.
- OSS/cloud asset persistence must not cause canvas content to disappear. Canvas state should store durable asset URLs when available.
- Never overwrite restored `lovart-canvas-boards` with the initial default board during page startup. Persistence writes must wait until restore is complete.
- Multi-device/cloud merge fixes must not drop projects or project contents just because another client has an older snapshot.
- Only explicit user deletion may remove a project, image, text item, shape, conversation, or history entry. Deletions should continue using deletion markers where applicable so old cloud state cannot revive deleted items.

Before changing canvas project persistence, test at least:

1. Create multiple projects, return home, re-enter professional mode: all projects remain.
2. Rename and reorder projects, refresh: order and names remain.
3. Add content to different projects, switch between them, refresh: each project keeps its own content.
4. Delete one project or item, refresh/cloud sync: only that deleted data stays gone.
